<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-10T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="48" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/58⅜:
                                    Telegram</note>
                                <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss></hi></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rio
                                                de Janeiro</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-10T15:00:00-03:00">June 10, 1940—3 p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 3:11
                                        p.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>259. The German and Russian and notably the Russian broadcasts
                                    are talking a lot about our alleged imperialistic designs in
                                    Latin <pb facs="0059" n="47" xml:id="pg_47"/> America under
                                    cover of acquiring air bases; and the Germans are stressing the
                                    trips of Colonel Miller and Captain Spears.</p>
                                <p>The local Germans are attempting to tie up the approaching visits
                                    of the <hi rend="italic">Quincy</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Wichita</hi> with all that.<note n="61" xml:id="d48fn1">See
                                        section entitled “Concern of the United States over Nazi
                                        activities in Uruguay; visits of United States naval vessels
                                        to the eastern coast of South America’ <ref target="#pg_1147">pp. 1147</ref> ff.</note></p>
                                <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi></signed></closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>